##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "unionTables.pl",
  "PGchoicemacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

##############################################

Context("Point");
Context()->parens->set("[" => {type => "Interval", close => "]"});
Context()->parens->set("{" => {type => "Set", close => "}"});
Context()->parens->set("<" => {type => "Vector", close => ">"});

$a=random(3,7,2);
$b=random(2,6,2);
$c=$a*$b;

$x1=random(1,3,1)*$b;
$y1=(-$a*$x1-$c)/$b+random(1,5,1);

$x2=random(-3,-1,1)*$b;
$y2=(-$a*$x2-$c)/$b;

$x3=0;
$y3=-$a+random(1,5,1);

$x4 = random(-3,-1,1) * $b;
while ($x4==$x2) {$x4 = random(-3,-1,1)*$b;}
$y4=(-$a*$x4-$c)/$b;

($pt[0],$pt[1],$pt[2],$pt[3]) = (Point($x1,$y1),Point($x2,$y2),Point($x3,$y3),Point($x4,$y4));


$mc = new_checkbox_multiple_choice();
$mc -> qa (
"Which of the following ordered pairs are solutions to the given equation? There may be more than
one correct answer.", 
"\( $pt[1]\)$BR",                
"\( $pt[3]\)$BR",
);
$mc -> extra(
"\( $pt[0]\)$BR",
"\( $pt[2]\)$BR",
);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());
BEGIN_PGML
Consider the equation

    [` [$a]x+[$b]y=-[$c]`]

[@ $mc -> print_q() @]*

    [@ $mc -> print_a() @]*

END_PGML

##############################################

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 0;

ANS( checkbox_cmp( $mc->correct_ans() ) );

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

We substitute in each ordered pair's [`x`]- and [`y`]-values into the equation [` [$a]x+[$b]y=-[$c]`], and see whether the resulting equation is true.

In two cases, [`([$x2],[$y2])`] and [`([$x4],[$y4])`], we have true equations:

        [`\begin{aligned}
    [$a]([$x2])+[$b]([$y2]) & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c] & [$a]([$x4])+[$b]([$y4]) & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c]\\
    [$a*$x2]+[$b*$y2] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c] & [$a*$x4]+[$b*$y4] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c]\\
    [$a*$x2+$b*$y2] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c] & [$a*$x4+$b*$y4] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c]\\
    \end{aligned}`]

So [`([$x2],[$y2])`] and [`([$x4],[$y4])`] are solutions to the given equation.

In the other two cases, [`([$x1],[$y1])`] and [`([$x3],[$y3])`], we have false equations:

    [`\begin{aligned}
    [$a]([$x1])+[$b]([$y1]) & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c] & [$a]([$x3])+[$b]([$y3]) & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c]\\
    [$a*$x1]+[$b*$y1] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c] & [$a*$x3]+[$b*$y3] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c]\\
    [$a*$x1+$b*$y1] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c] & [$a*$x3+$b*$y3] & \stackrel{?}{=} -[$c]\\
    \end{aligned}`]

So [`([$x1],[$y1])`] and [`([$x3],[$y3])`] are not solutions.




END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();


